  156. /* Starts runtime_events. Needs to be called before
  157.    [caml_runtime_events_create_cursor]. Needs the runtime lock held to call and
  158.    will trigger a stop-the-world pause. Returns Val_unit. */
  159. CAMLextern value caml_runtime_events_start(void);

  161. /* Pauses runtime_events if not currently paused otherwise does nothing.
  162.    No new events (other than the pause itself) will be written to the ring
  163.    buffer by this domain immediately and all other domains soon. Needs the
  164.    runtime lock held to call as a pause event is written during this call.
  165.    Returns Val_unit. */
  166. CAMLextern value caml_runtime_events_pause(void);

  168. /* Resumes runtime_events if currently paused otherwise does nothing. New events
  169.    (as well as a resume event) will be written to this domain immediately and
  170.    all other domains soon. Needs the runtime lock held to call as a resume event
  171.    is written during this call. Returns Val_unit. */
  172. CAMLextern value caml_runtime_events_resume(void);

  227. ‌#define RUNTIME_EVENTS_MAX_CUSTOM_EVENTS (1 << 13)
  228. ‌#define RUNTIME_EVENTS_NUM_ALLOC_BUCKETS 20
  229. ‌#define RUNTIME_EVENTS_MAX_MSG_LENGTH (1 << 10)

  231. /* event header fields (for runtime events):
  232. - length (10 bits)
  233. - runtime or user event (1 bit)
  234. - event type (4 bits)
  235. - event id (13 bits)
  236. */

  238. ‌#define RUNTIME_EVENTS_ITEM_LENGTH(header) \
  239.         (((header) >> 54) & ((1UL << 10) - 1))
  240. ‌#define RUNTIME_EVENTS_ITEM_IS_RUNTIME(header) !((header) & (1ULL << 53))
  241. ‌#define RUNTIME_EVENTS_ITEM_IS_USER(header) ((header) & (1ULL << 53))
  242. ‌#define RUNTIME_EVENTS_ITEM_TYPE(header) (((header) >> 49) & ((1UL << 4) - 1))
  243. ‌#define RUNTIME_EVENTS_ITEM_ID(header) (((header) >> 36) & ((1UL << 13) - 1))

  245. ‌#define RUNTIME_EVENTS_HEADER(length, is_runtime, type, event_id) \
  246.          (((uint64_t)(length)) << 54) | \
  247.          ((is_runtime) ? 0 : (1ULL << 53)) | \
  248.          ((uint64_t)(type)) << 49 | \
  249.          ((uint64_t)(event_id)) << 36;

  251. /* Set up runtime_events (and check if we need to start it immediately).
  252.    Called from startup* */
  253. void caml_runtime_events_init(void);

  255. /* Destroy all allocated runtime_events structures and clear up the ring.
  256.    Called from [caml_sys_exit] */
  257. void caml_runtime_events_destroy(void);

  259. /* Handle safely re-initialising the runtime_events structures
  260.    in a forked child */

  263. /* Returns the location of the runtime_events for the current process if started
  264.    or NULL otherwise */

  267. /* Functions for putting runtime data on to the runtime_events. These are all
  268.    internal to the runtime, except for caml_ev_lifecycle which is needed in
  269.    otherlibs/unix/fork.c so must be declared CAMLextern in order to work on
  270.    Cygwin. */

  272. void caml_ev_end(ev_runtime_phase phase);
  273. void caml_ev_counter(ev_runtime_counter counter, uint64_t val);
  274. CAMLextern void caml_ev_lifecycle(ev_lifecycle lifecycle, int64_t data);

  276. /* caml_ev_alloc records the (bucketed) size of allocations into the major heap.
  277.    It appears only in alloc_shr and caml_shared_try_alloc. These buckets are
  278.    meant to be flushed explicitly by the caller through the caml_ev_alloc_flush
  279.    function. Until then the buckets are just updated until flushed.
  280. */
  281. void caml_ev_alloc(uint64_t sz);
  282. void caml_ev_alloc_flush(void);


  285. /* Allocate a unique ID for the event and construct its value: there are at
